  "prompt": "What is the difference between ordinary differential equations and partial differential equations?",
  "response": "Let me explain the key differences between ordinary differential equations (ODEs) and partial differential equations (PDEs):\n\nOrdinary Differential Equations (ODEs):\n1. Involve derivatives with respect to a single independent variable\n2. Describe relationships between a function and its derivatives\n3. Typically involve functions of one variable\n4. Example: dy/dx = f(x,y)\n5. Solutions are functions of a single variable\n6. Simpler to solve and analyze\n7. Common in describing systems that change over time or in a single dimension\n\nPartial Differential Equations (PDEs):\n1. Involve partial derivatives with respect to multiple independent variables\n2. Describe relationships between a function and its partial derivatives\n3. Involve functions of multiple variables\n4. Example: \u2202u/\u2202x + \u2202u/\u2202y = f(x,y)\n5. Solutions are functions of multiple variables\n6. More complex to solve and analyze\n7. Common in describing systems with multiple dimensions, like heat flow, wave propagation, quantum mechanics\n\nKey distinguishing feature: Number of independent variables and type of derivatives used.\n\nExample:\n- ODE: Temperature change over time\n- PDE: Temperature distribution across a surface",
